In order to support the most appropriate energy policy decisions, an analytical method to jointly understand the driving forces behind the observed developments of (1) the energy-related CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_{2}$$\end{document} emissions, (2) the energy consumption and (3) the energy efficiency (the three magnitudes for which the main energy and climate targets are defined) is irremediably needed. In this paper, we develop a methodological framework to investigate the contributions of various influencing factors to the evolution of the energy-related CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_{2}$$\end{document} emissions between 1995 and 2017 both in Spain and in the EU28. In this way, within one comprehensive methodological framework, we are able to capture the role played by primary energy consumption and the renewable-energy share of the energy-mix in the developments of the energy-related CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_{2}$$\end{document} emissions.

In addition, the decomposition method that we propose takes into account jointly the effects that (1) the technical aspects of the physical energy system (analyzed through energy input–output models) and (2) the macro-level influencing factors traditionally employed (studied through IDA decomposition methods) have in the evolution of the energy-related CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_{2}$$\end{document} emissions both in Spain and in the EU28. Thus, we refer to this hybrid integrated approach, which benefits from the advantages of both SDA and IDA techniques, as input–output logarithmic mean Divisia index (IO-LMDI, hereafter) decomposition method. Further, with our methodological approach, we also provide an allocation diagram scheme for assigning the responsibility of primary energy requirements and CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_{2}$$\end{document} emissions to the end-use sectors including both economic and non-productive sectors. Moreover, we are able to (3) analyze more potential influencing factors than those typically examined. In addition, we (4) proceed in a way that reconciles energy intensity and energy efficiency metrics. Finally, we (5) distinguish between technical and observed end-use energy efficiency taking into account potential rebound effects and other factors. Therefore, we believe that our work represents a novelty and offers clear value added to past studies devoted to the study of the energy-related CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_{2}$$\end{document} emissions trends both in Spain and in the EU28.

To report of our findings, we make a distinction between two clear sub-periods: 1995-2007 and 2007-2017. In the first mentioned sub-period, the CO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
